AB  - The paper deals with a neoclassical growth model of an economy which has to import all the natural resources needed as nonsubstitutable industrial inputs in proportion to gross output. Depending on the internal and external conditions, one of two contrasting economic paths prevails: (1) a path with rising terms of trade and increasing capital/output ratio and (2) a path with falling terms of trade and declining capital/output ratio that could lead to ‘immiserising growth.’ Certain boundary conditions that distinguish the two cases are discussed.
